ac Beatha</b> ‘son of life’, i.e. ‘man of religion’, used as a personal name. Compare Irish   McVey   and   McAbee  ."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm Macbeth 1st Earl of Ross was born in 1158, in Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Máel Coluim Mac Alaxandair, was 39 and his mother, Mariotte MacGillebride, was 39. He had at least 1 son with ? Nic Intagart de Ross. He died in Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1158–":"1158–Surnud","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1146–1156":"1146–1156","1146–Female":"1146–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1170–1251":"1170–1251","1120–1168":"1120–1168","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1158":"1158","1168":"1168","1146":"1146","1156":"1156","1155":"1155","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","1251":"1251","1152":"1152","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Applecross, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Applecross, Ross-shire, Scotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland","strathnaver  kirkcubrightshire scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Moray, Scotland":"Mo